Residents from Philippi in Cape Town took to the streets on Saturday, in the pouring rain, to protest against femicide and gender-based violence. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The cold and rain did not deter them from having their voices heard. Hundreds of Philippi residents marched to the Nyanga Police Station in protest of violence against women and children. This after 17-year-old schoolgirl Amahle Quku was found murdered and dumped in a field close to her home in Browns Farm. READ: Philippi residents demand justice for Amahle Quku She was one of four women killed in the Western Cape this month, and a 7-year-old was also murdered. In all five cases, the men arrested were known to their victims. Quku’s parents are struggling to raise money to bury their daughter.